highest quality vbr is best imo. vbr just calculates when the low density sound can be carried by lower bitrates and leaves bitspace for the "noisy" parts so that quality isn't compromised (of course it's still lossy as long as it is not flac codec) and the filesize would be much lower than 320cbr. I didn't get any difference between vbr and cbr through my experience. Except 128kbs. Very interesting thing about bitrates is, if the ripper knows what is he doing, even 128 kbits would be sufficent in some cases. This is a very rare thing these days. But it reminds me that bitrates isn't everything.

My own 2 cents, I prefer FLAC, since it's easy to convert into lossless and then from there, to any compressed version I prefer. I don't really download 320 anymore, unless there's absolutely no other choice.
